    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Mortgage Renewal During Divorce or Separation: What Every Canadian Needs to Know</h1>
    <p class="text-lg mb-8" style="color: var(--muted-foreground)">Updated March 2026 · 7-minute read</p>

    <p class="mb-6 text-base leading-relaxed">Navigating a mortgage renewal at the same time as a separation or divorce adds legal, emotional, and financial complexity to an already challenging period. The decisions you make about the mortgage have long-lasting financial consequences — and they intersect in important ways with your separation agreement, property division, and future housing plans. This guide explains your options clearly and helps you understand what to prioritize.</p>

    <div class="rounded-lg p-5 mb-8" style="background: var(--accent); border-left: 4px solid var(--secondary)">
      <p class="font-bold mb-2">Get Both Legal and Mortgage Advice Early</p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">The advice in this guide is educational. Separation and divorce involve complex legal considerations that vary significantly by province, relationship type (married vs. common-law), and length of relationship. Consult both a family law lawyer and a mortgage broker — ideally 6+ months before your maturity date if your renewal is approaching during a separation.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">The Three Main Options When Separating with a Joint Mortgage</h2>

    <div class="space-y-5 mb-8">
      <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 2px solid var(--secondary); background: var(--card)">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3" style="color: var(--secondary)">Option 1: One Spouse Buys Out the Other</h3>
        <p class="mb-3 leading-relaxed text-sm">The most common outcome when both parties want a clean break and one person wants to keep the home. The buying spouse takes over full ownership of the property and the mortgage, and pays the departing spouse their share of the home's equity.</p>
        <p class="mb-3 leading-relaxed text-sm"><strong>What this requires:</strong> A full refinance — not a simple renewal. The buying spouse must qualify under the mortgage stress test <em>on their own income</em> for the full mortgage balance (or the new balance after equity is extracted to pay out the departing spouse). This is the biggest hurdle: qualifying on a single income for a mortgage that was previously serviced by two incomes.</p>
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed"><strong>Legal requirement:</strong> A signed separation agreement (or court order) confirming the property division is typically required by lenders before proceeding with the buyout refinance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3" style="color: var(--primary)">Option 2: Both Parties Remain on the Mortgage</h3>
        <p class="mb-3 leading-relaxed text-sm">Less clean emotionally but sometimes the most financially practical option — particularly when one spouse cannot qualify alone for the full mortgage, or when property prices mean neither party can afford to buy a comparable home independently.</p>
        <p class="mb-3 leading-relaxed text-sm">This may involve one person continuing to live in the home (and ideally paying the mortgage) while both remain legally liable for the debt. At renewal, the mortgage can simply be renewed — no change to the borrowers required. The key risk: both parties remain exposed to each other's financial behavior for the mortgage's duration. Missed payments by one party affect both credit scores.</p>
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed"><strong>Exit strategy:</strong> This usually works best when both parties agree on a defined timeline — e.g., remaining co-borrowers for 2–3 years while the children finish school, then selling or doing a buyout at that point.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-lg p-5" style="border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--card)">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3" style="color: var(--primary)">Option 3: Sell the Property</h3>
        <p class="mb-3 leading-relaxed text-sm">When neither party can afford to maintain the property alone, or when a clean financial break is the priority, selling the home and splitting the proceeds is often the most straightforward resolution. Any remaining mortgage balance is paid off at sale using the property's proceeds.</p>
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed"><strong>Mortgage consideration:</strong> If you're selling before your term ends, a prepayment penalty will apply. Variable rate mortgages carry only 3 months' interest penalty — significantly less than fixed-rate IRD penalties. If your maturity date is approaching, it may be worth waiting to sell until after the renewal date to avoid the penalty entirely.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Renewing While Actively Separated: What Happens?</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">If your mortgage term is expiring while you're in the middle of a separation — before a separation agreement is finalized — things get complicated. Lenders will typically still renew the existing mortgage with all current borrowers on the same terms. Both parties must sign the renewal, which can be challenging if communication has broken down.</p>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Options in this scenario:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2 leading-relaxed">
      <li>Both parties sign the renewal to avoid a maturity default while the separation is being negotiated (most common practical approach)</li>
      <li>One party applies for a court order authorizing them to sign on behalf of both if the other refuses</li>
      <li>In extreme cases, the mortgage goes into default at maturity — which is damaging for both parties and should be avoided</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">If you cannot get both parties to cooperate on a renewal, seek legal advice and contact your lender immediately to explain the situation. Lenders will sometimes accommodate a short extension while legal matters are resolved.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Qualifying on a Single Income</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">The most common challenge in buyout scenarios is qualifying for the mortgage on a single income. Joint mortgages are often sized to reflect combined household income — which means neither party alone can necessarily qualify for the full amount.</p>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Strategies that can help qualify on a single income:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2 leading-relaxed">
      <li><strong>Spousal or child support income:</strong> Court-ordered spousal or child support payments you're receiving can typically be counted as qualifying income — but lenders want to see a signed separation agreement or court order, and usually require the support to have been received for at least 6 months.</li>
      <li><strong>Rental income:</strong> If you plan to rent out a portion of the home (basement suite, for example), rental income from the subject property can supplement your qualifying income under most lender guidelines.</li>
      <li><strong>Lower mortgage amount:</strong> If the equity is divided at sale and one spouse takes a net cash payout, the remaining mortgage balance is reduced. A smaller mortgage is easier to qualify for on a single income.</li>
      <li><strong>Longer amortization:</strong> Extending the amortization (where lender allows) reduces the monthly payment and therefore the qualifying income required. Note: this increases total interest cost over time.</li>
      <li><strong>B-lender programs:</strong> If A-lender qualification isn't possible, B-lenders sometimes have more flexible debt ratio calculations or can accept higher TDS ratios for specific situations.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Adding or Removing a Co-Borrower = Full Refinance</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">This is a critical legal and financial fact that many separating couples don't realize until it's too late: <strong>removing someone from a mortgage — regardless of what your separation agreement says — requires a full refinance</strong>. You cannot simply remove a co-borrower at renewal by signing a form. The mortgage must be fully re-underwritten in the remaining borrower's name.</p>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">This refinance:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 space-y-1 leading-relaxed">
      <li>Requires a full mortgage application and stress test qualification</li>
      <li>Requires a new appraisal of the property (at borrower's cost, typically $300–$500)</li>
      <li>Requires legal work — a lawyer or notary must prepare the documentation ($800–$1,500+)</li>
      <li>Triggers a prepayment penalty if done mid-term on a closed mortgage</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">A separation agreement that says "Jane will take the house and John will be removed from the mortgage" does not automatically make this happen. John remains legally on the hook for the mortgage until the refinance is completed and registered. This exposes John to credit risk (if Jane misses payments) and mortgage liability until the legal change is finalized.</p>

    <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Planning the timing of the buyout refinance to coincide with — or immediately after — your mortgage maturity date eliminates the prepayment penalty. If your maturity date is approaching, this is a significant factor in your planning.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">What Lenders Need: The Separation Agreement</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Lenders universally require a signed separation agreement or court-approved divorce order before processing a buyout refinance or any change to mortgage ownership. The agreement must clearly address:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-1 leading-relaxed">
      <li>Who is keeping the property</li>
      <li>The equity split and how the departing spouse is compensated</li>
      <li>Any spousal or child support obligations (relevant for income qualification)</li>
      <li>Any other conditions affecting financial obligations</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">Lenders will not process a buyout based on an informal email agreement or verbal understanding. The legal document must exist. This is another reason to engage a family law lawyer early in the process — the separation agreement is a prerequisite to resolving the mortgage, not a follow-up step.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4" style="color: var(--primary)">Timeline and Recommended Approach</h2>

    <ol class="list-decimal list-inside mb-8 space-y-3 leading-relaxed">
      <li><strong>Engage a family law lawyer immediately</strong> — before making any mortgage decisions. The legal and financial issues are intertwined.</li>
      <li><strong>Consult a mortgage broker</strong> — to understand what each party can qualify for independently, what a buyout would cost, and how to time the mortgage changes optimally.</li>
      <li><strong>Identify your mortgage maturity date</strong> — to determine whether it makes sense to wait until maturity to avoid prepayment penalties.</li>
      <li><strong>Finalize your separation agreement</strong> — including the property division and support provisions needed by lenders.</li>
      <li><strong>Execute the mortgage change</strong> (buyout refinance or sale) at the most financially advantageous time.</li>
    </ol>

